"ce:surname": "Khamdahsag", "ce:indexed-name": "Khamdahsag P."}, "@seq": "4", "ce:initials": "P.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Khamdahsag", "@auid": "55255193500", "ce:indexed-name": "Khamdahsag P."}]}, {"affiliation": {"country": "Thailand", "postal-code": "12121", "@afid": "60012521", "@country": "tha", "city": "Pathumthani", "organization": [{"$": "Center of Excellence in Environmental Catalysis and Adsorption"}, {"$": "Department of Chemical Engineering"}, {"$": "Faculty of Engineering"}, {"$": "Thammasat University"}], "affiliation-id": {"@afid": "60012521", "@dptid": "108420469"}, "@dptid": "108420469"}, "author": [{"preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "N.", "ce:initials": "N.", "ce:surname": "Grisdanurak", "ce:indexed-name": "Grisdanurak N."}, "@seq": "5", "ce:initials": "N.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Grisdanurak", "@auid": "23008001400", "ce:indexed-name": "Grisdanurak N."}]}], "citation-title": "Co-benefit of silver nanoparticle and titanium dioxide for elemental mercury adsorption", "abstracts": "\u00a9 2016 IEEE.Titanium dioxide-supported silver nanoparticles was synthesized by a facile method and studied as a sorbents for elemental mercury (Hg\u00b0). The concentration of deposited silver nanoparticles was in the range of 0.1-5.0% weight of titanium dioxide powder. XRD and TEM results confirmed that silver nanoparticles with a diameter size ranging from 2-5 nm were successfully deposited on the surface of titanium dioxide. The capacity of the synthesized sorbents in capturing elemental mercury were tested by exposing sorbent to Hg vapor in a static system comparing with the original titanium dioxide and silver nanoparticles. The performance of titanium dioxide for elemental mercury was significantly increased when silver cooperated. Moreover, the capacity of 5.0% silver loading was comparable with the original silver nanoparticles. Through periodic density function theory study it was found that the synergetic effect of titanium dioxide support and silver nanoparticles could presumably due to the electron acceptor characteristic of TiO2-supported silver nanoparticles to promote the Hg\u00b0 adsorption via electron transferred from the Hg\u00b0 to the deposited silver nanoparticle and the entire TiO2 support.", "correspondence": {"affiliation": {"country": "Thailand", "address-part": "Paholyothin Rd.", "postal-code": "12120", "@country": "tha", "city": "Pathumthani", "organization": [{"$": "National Nanotechnology Center"}, {"$": "National Science and Technology Development Agency"}, {"$": "Thailand Science Park"}]}, "person": {"ce:initials": "S.", "ce:surname": "Chaleawlert-Umpon", "ce:indexed-name": "Chaleawlert-Umpon S."}}, "citation-info": {"citation-type": {"@code": "cp"}, "citation-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "abstract-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}}, "source": {"translated-sourcetitle": {"$": "16th International Conference on Nanotechnology - IEEE NANO 2016", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "volisspag": {"pagerange": {"@first": "438", "@last": "441"}}, "@type": "p", "isbn": {"$": "9781509039142", "@type": "electronic", "@length": "13"}, "additional-srcinfo": {"conferenceinfo": {"confevent": {"confname": "16th IEEE International Conference on Nanotechnology - IEEE NANO 2016", "confsponsors": {"confsponsor": [{"$": "et al."}, {"$": "Mitsubishi Electric"}, {"$": "NEC"}, {"$": "SONY"}, {"$": "Sysmex Corporation"}, {"$": "TReK"}], "@complete": "n"}, "confnumber": "16", "confcatnumber": "CFP16NAN-USB", "confseriestitle": "IEEE International Conference on Nanotechnology", "conflocation": {"@country": "jpn", "city": "Sendai"}, "confcode": "125071", "confdate": {"enddate": {"@day": "25", "@year": "2016", "@month": "08"}, "startdate": {"@day": "22", "@year": "2016", "@month": "08"}}, "conftheme": "Green Nanotechnology for a Sustainable Society"}}}, "sourcetitle": "16th International Conference on Nanotechnology - IEEE NANO 2016", "publ